sentences: Pepper J. Keenan (born May 8, 1967) is an American guitarist and vocalist, best known for his work with heavy metal bands Corrosion of Conformity and Down.
He joined Corrosion of Conformity in 1989, but did not become the lead singer until the recording of Deliverance in 1994.

Their first U.S. tour with the reunited lineup, supporting Clutch, was announced in July 2015.
No Cross No Crown, the bands latest album to date, was released in 2018 and features Keenan on vocals and guitar.
Keenan was a founding member of Down in 1991 along with Pantera's Phil Anselmo, Eyehategod's Jimmy Bower, and Crowbar's Kirk Windstein and Todd Strange.
In 1995, Down released their debut album, NOLA.
The band went on indefinite hiatus in 1996 but returned three years later with Pantera bassist Rex Brown replacing Strange.
In 2002, Down released their second album Down II: A Bustle in Your Hedgerow.
Following a second hiatus, Down released their third album entitled Down III: Over the Under in 2007.
Down released their fourth album Down IV Part I – The Purple EP in September 2012 and Down IV – Part II of a four-part series of EPs.

In addition to his contribution to the song "Tuesday's Gone" Pepper also appeared with Metallica onstage at the Download Festival in Donington, England in 2006 along with Matt Heafy of Trivium to provide additional vocals on the song "Die, Die My Darling" (a Misfits cover).
Keenan became the father of a daughter named Flannery Rose Keenan with his longtime girlfriend Anna Hrnjak on January 5, 2010.
Keenan was featured with his 1955 Chevy "Gasser" in a television episode of Big Easy Motors.
At a 2016 Corrosion of Conformity concert, Keenan dedicated the song "Vote with a Bullet" to the former US president.
